          "title": "Step 1",
          "content": "Step 1: Market Segmentation\nIn this first step, you will begin an exciting adventure to identify who your potential customers are and which markets could be the best match for your business idea. Start by brainstorming a diverse range of customer groups and market opportunities. Consider various types of people and businesses that might find value in what you plan to offer. This could include different age groups, interests, or industries that align with your product or service. Once you have created a comprehensive list, it’s time to focus on your top 6 to 12 markets that appear to be the most promising and viable for your business. After narrowing down your options, you will then gather primary market research. This means you will collect information directly from potential customers about their needs, preferences, and behaviors. Engaging with your target audience will provide you with valuable insights and help you understand what they truly want. This step is essential because having a clear understanding of your target market will empower you to make informed decisions as you continue on your entrepreneurial journey. Remember, viewing your business idea through the right lens can significantly influence your chances of success!\nContext recap: Step 1: Market Segmentation\nIn this first step, you will begin an exciting adventure to identify who your potential customers are and which markets could be the best match for your business idea. Start by brainstorming a diverse range of customer groups and market opportunities. Consider various types of people and businesses that might find value in what you plan to offer. This could include different age groups, interests, or industries that align with your product or service.\nWhy this matters: Step 1 helps learners in Business connect ideas from Disciplined Entrepreneurship to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
